          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Portuguese Prime Minister Luis Montenegro gestures during a debate preceding a confidence motion vote at the Portuguese parliament in Lisbon. Credits: AP Photo/ Armando Franca</i></p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Portugal is on track for its third election in three years. PM Luis Montenegro's center-right government <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-13-03-2025-h1-1-lost-a-confidence-vote?source=website" target="_blank">lost a confidence vote</a> in parliament. The vote follows controversy over potential conflicts of interest involving Montenegro’s family law firm, which has ties to a government contractor. While Montenegro denies wrongdoing, opposition parties, including the Socialist Party, demanded more transparency.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;filter:blur(5px);">Montenegro’s administration lasted just 11 months. It mirrors the political instability that led to the previous election in March 2024. The last one was triggered by corruption allegations surrounding former Socialist PM António Costa’s chief of staff. Montenegro denied wrongdoings and claimed he placed control of the firm entirely in the hands of his wife and children in 2022.
       </p>
        </mj-text>
